const artsData=[{emoji:"🧵",name:"Banarasi Silk Weaving",location:"Varanasi",desc:"The most prized silk in India — interwoven with real gold (zari) and silver threads into brocade patterns. GI-tagged with 1,200 years of history. Banarasi sarees are worn at weddings across India and woven on handlooms in Varanasi's ancient lanes."},{emoji:"🪡",name:"Chikankari Embroidery",location:"Lucknow",desc:"Delicate white-on-white shadow embroidery on cotton and chiffon, perfected in the Nawabi courts of Awadh. 36 distinct stitches, each with a specific name. A single saree can take 3–6 months. Lucknow's most globally recognized cultural export."},{emoji:"🏺",name:"Blue Pottery of Khurja",location:"Khurja, Bulandshahr",desc:"Distinctive turquoise-blue glazed pottery using quartz, not clay. Persian origins brought by the Mughals. Khurja is the Pottery City of India producing 40% of India's ceramic tableware. A GI-protected heritage craft."},{emoji:"🪘",name:"Kathak Dance",location:"Lucknow & Varanasi",desc:"One of India's eight classical dance forms, born in UP's temples and refined in Nawabi courts. Known for lightning-fast spins (chakkar), intricate footwork (tatkar) and expressive storytelling (abhinaya). Two gharanas — Lucknow and Varanasi."},{emoji:"🔩",name:"Brass Craft of Moradabad",location:"Moradabad",desc:"Moradabad — Brass City — produces 85% of India's brass handicraft exports. Intricate engravings on vases, lamps and decorative items sent to 100+ countries. Over 1 million artisans employed in this GI-protected heritage craft."},{emoji:"🪞",name:"Agra Marble Inlay",location:"Agra",desc:"The same pietra dura technique used in the Taj Mahal, practiced by descendants of Mughal-era craftsmen. Semi-precious stones — lapis lazuli, malachite, carnelian — set into white marble in floral patterns. Every piece is a miniature Taj Mahal."}];

const traditionsData=[{emoji:"🔥",name:"Ganga Aarti, Varanasi",location:"Dashashwamedh Ghat, Varanasi",desc:"Every evening at sunset, five priests perform an elaborate fire worship with massive camphor-lit lamps, conch shells and Vedic chanting. The ritual has continued unbroken for centuries. Best witnessed from a boat on the Ganges at dusk."},{emoji:"🌸",name:"Braj Holi — Lathmar Holi",location:"Mathura, Vrindavan & Barsana",desc:"The Braj region celebrates Holi for 40 days in its most ancient form. Lathmar Holi at Barsana sees women joyfully beat men with sticks. Phoolon ki Holi at Vrindavan is a riot of rose petals. Holi here predates recorded history."},{emoji:"🪔",name:"Dev Deepawali",location:"Varanasi",desc:"On Kartik Purnima (15 days after Diwali), all 84 ghats of Varanasi are illuminated with over one million earthen lamps. Gods are said to descend to bathe in the Ganges. The reflection of a million flames on the river is India's most breathtaking spectacle."},{emoji:"🎭",name:"Ram Leela",location:"Ramnagar (Varanasi) & Ayodhya",desc:"Month-long dramatic re-enactment of the Ramayana during Navratri. Ramnagar's Ram Leela — patronized by the Maharaja of Varanasi — is UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage, performed across 25 km with 100,000 nightly spectators."},{emoji:"🕌",name:"Kumbh Mela",location:"Prayagraj",desc:"The world's largest religious gathering, held every 12 years at Triveni Sangam. Over 50 million pilgrims attend the Maha Kumbh. Naga Sadhus march in procession to bathe on the most auspicious dates. The greatest spectacle of human faith."},{emoji:"🎊",name:"Lucknow Mahotsav",location:"Lucknow",desc:"Annual multi-day festival celebrating the Nawabi heritage of Awadh. Classical music, Kathak performances, ghazal evenings, Awadhi cuisine and chikankari exhibitions. A celebration of tehzeeb — the refined Lucknowi culture of courteous elegance."}];

const cuisinesData=[{emoji:"🍛",name:"Awadhi Dum Biryani",region:"Lucknow — Nawabi Legacy",desc:"The original dum biryani — meat and rice slow-cooked in a sealed pot with saffron, kewra and whole spices. The Nawabs of Awadh elevated biryani to high art. Lucknow's version is subtler and more fragrant, each grain of rice perfectly separate."},{emoji:"🫕",name:"Galouti Kebab",region:"Lucknow",desc:"Invented for a toothless Nawab who could no longer chew. 160 spices ground into meat so tender it dissolves on the tongue. Served on wafer-thin ulte tawa paratha. The most delicate kebab ever created by any culinary tradition."},{emoji:"🫓",name:"Bedai & Jalebi",region:"Agra & Western UP",desc:"The quintessential UP breakfast. Bedai — crisp puris stuffed with spiced urad dal — with spicy aloo sabzi and syrupy orange jalebis. The combination at Agra's Deviram's has been a morning ritual since the Mughal era."},{emoji:"🥣",name:"Kachori Sabzi",region:"Varanasi & Statewide",desc:"Varanasi's iconic street breakfast — crisp kachoris with spiced dal, two differently seasoned aloo sabzis and green chutney. Eaten on stone steps beside ancient temples at dawn. The taste is inseparable from the experience of Kashi."},{emoji:"🍮",name:"Rabri & Malaiyo",region:"Varanasi & Mathura",desc:"Rabri — thickened milk simmered into rich layers. Malaiyo — a winter-only cloud-like dessert from churned milk foam, garnished with saffron and pistachios. Available only in Varanasi from October to February."},{emoji:"🍬",name:"Petha of Agra",region:"Agra",desc:"White ash gourd preserved in sugar syrup until translucent and crystalline. A GI-tagged confection unique to Agra. Agra's Panchi Petha has been making it since 1860 in safed, angoori and kesar variants."},{emoji:"🧆",name:"Awadhi Tehri & Pulao",region:"Awadh Region",desc:"Fragrant vegetarian pulao with potatoes and whole spices, cooked dum style with saffron and ghee. Tehri was the vegetarian biryani of the Nawabs' Hindu courtiers. A deeply comforting dish of extraordinary elegance."},{emoji:"🥛",name:"Mathura Peda & Vrindavan Khurchan",region:"Mathura–Vrindavan",desc:"Mathura's peda — dense milk sweets made for 400 years as prasad for Lord Krishna. Vrindavan's khurchan is scraped condensed milk with cardamom. Every Braj temple distributes these as divine offering."},{emoji:"🌿",name:"Chaat — Samosa & Aloo Tikki",region:"Statewide",desc:"UP invented India's chaat culture. Varanasi's tamatar chaat, Lucknow's basket chaat, Agra's dalmoth — each city has its signature. The samosa in its modern form was perfected in UP's bazaars. No state has done more to shape India's street food."},{emoji:"🫙",name:"Baati Chokha",region:"Bundelkhand Region",desc:"In UP's Bundelkhand region, baked wheat baati with roasted vegetable chokha and ghee is the staple. Hearty, smoky and deeply satisfying — shaped by the rocky Vindhya landscape and warrior Bundela culture."},{emoji:"🫖",name:"Imarti & Makkhan Malai",region:"Lucknow & Statewide",desc:"Imarti — a swirling orange sweet deeper and more complex than jalebi. Makkhan malai — airy whipped cream dessert available only in winter mornings in Varanasi. Both emblematic of UP's Mughal-era sweet-making tradition."},{emoji:"🍙",name:"Anarsa",region:"Festival Sweet — Eastern UP",desc:"Rice flour sweets rolled in poppy seeds and deep-fried. A Diwali season specialty. The crispy poppy seed coating with soft rice interior is a unique texture found in this ancient belt of the Ganga plains."}];

